160;</span></span>, pp. 108\xe2\x80\x93115</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-price-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-price_12-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-price_12-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-price_12-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-price_12-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-price_12-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Price, Glanville (1984). <i>The French language: past and present</i>. London: Grant and Cutler Ltd.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.aufirst=Glanville&amp;rft.aulast=Price&amp;rft.btitle=The+French+language%3A+past+and+present&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Grant+and+Cutler+Ltd&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"Na" is a <a href="/wiki/Contraction_(grammar)" title="Contraction (grammar)">contraction</a> of "em" (in) + "a" (the), the form "em a" is never used, it is always replaced by "na". The same happens with other prepositions: "de" (of) + o/a/os/as (singular and plural forms for "the" in masculine and feminine) = do, da, dos, das; etc.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Verb; literally means "to put in mouth"</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">See <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_in_Africa" class="mw-redirect" title="Portuguese in Africa">Portuguese in Africa</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">See <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_language_in_Asia" title="Portuguese language in Asia">Portuguese in Asia and Oceania</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">See <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_where_Portuguese_is_an_official_language" class="mw-redirect" title="List of countries where Portuguese is an official language">List of countries where Portuguese is an official language</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-18"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=ron">1993 Statistical Abstract</a> of Israel reports 250,000 speakers of Romanian in Israel, while the 1995 census puts the total figure of the Israeli population at 5,548,523</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.eurojewcong.org/ejc/news.php?id_article=110">"Reports of about 300,000 Jews who left the country after WW2"</a>. Eurojewcong.org<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2010-11-06</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=Reports+of+about+300%2C000+Jews+who+left+the+country+after+WW2&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Eurojewcong.org&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.eurojewcong.org%2Fejc%2Fnews.php%3Fid_article%3D110&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Encarta-20"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Encarta_20-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://uk.encarta.msn.com/encnet/features/dictionary/dictionaryhome.aspx">"Encarta Dictionary"</a>. Microsoft Encarta 2006<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2009-11-16</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=Encarta+Dictionary&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Microsoft+Encarta+2006&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fuk.encarta.msn.com%2Fencnet%2Ffeatures%2Fdictionary%2Fdictionaryhome.aspx&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-ethnologue1-21"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-ethnologue1_21-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ethnologue.org/ethno_docs/distribution.asp?by=size">"Ethnologue"</a>. SIL Haley.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=Ethnologue&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=SIL+Haley&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.org%2Fethno_docs%2Fdistribution.asp%3Fby%3Dsize&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/508379/Romance-languages">"Romance languages"</a>. <i>Encyclop\xc3\xa6dia Britannica</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2 December</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.atitle=Romance+languages&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Encyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2FEBchecked%2Ftopic%2F508379%2FRomance-languages&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"Sardos etiam, qui non Latii sunt sed Latiis associandi videntur, eiciamus, quoniam soli sine proprio vulgari esse videntur, gramaticam tanquam simie homines imitantes: nam domus nova et dominus meus locuntur." ("Let us ignore the Sardinians, then, who are not <a href="/wiki/Latins" title="Latins">Latins</a> but appear to be associated with them, because they alone seem to lack their own common tongue, rather imitating (Latin) grammar as monkeys do men: For they say \'domus nova\' and \'dominus meus\'.") It is unclear whether this <abbr title="indicative mood">indic.</abbr>tes that Sardinian still had a two-case system at the time; modern Sardinian lacks grammatical case.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://donh.best.vwh.net/Languages/novlatin.html">"NEO-ROMANTICISM IN LANGUAGE PLANNING (Edo BERNASCONI)"</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=NEO-ROMANTICISM+IN+LANGUAGE+PLANNING+%28Edo+BERNASCONI%29&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdonh.best.vwh.net%2FLanguages%2Fnovlatin.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://donh.best.vwh.net/Languages/novlatin2.html">"NEO-ROMANTICISM IN LANGUAGE PLANNING (Edo BERNASCONI)"</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=NEO-ROMANTICISM+IN+LANGUAGE+PLANNING+%28Edo+BERNASCONI%29&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdonh.best.vwh.net%2FLanguages%2Fnovlatin2.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-26"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Peano, Giuseppe (1903). <i>De Latino Sine Flexione. Lingua Auxiliare Internationale</i> <a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="http://www.gutenberg.org/files/35803/35803-h/35803-h.htm">[2]</a>, <i>Revista de Mathematica</i> (<i>Revue de Math\xc3\xa9matiques</i>), Tomo VIII, pp. 74\xe2\x80\x9383. Fratres Bocca Editores: Torino.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-27"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20080610171257/http://www.cix.co.uk/~morven/lang/breath.html">"Eall fhoil de Bhreathanach"</a>. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.cix.co.uk/~morven/lang/breath.html">the original</a> on June 10, 2008.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=Eall+fhoil+de+Bhreathanach&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cix.co.uk%2F~morven%2Flang%2Fbreath.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-28"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Henrik Theiling (2007-10-28). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.kunstsprachen.de/s17/s_02.html">"\xc3\x9erj\xc3\xb3trunn: A North Romance Language: History"</a>. Kunstsprachen.de<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2010-11-06</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.au=Henrik+Theiling&amp;rft.btitle=%C3%9Erj%C3%B3trunn%3A+A+North+Romance+Language%3A+History&amp;rft.date=2007-10-28&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Kunstsprachen.de&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.kunstsprachen.de%2Fs17%2Fs_02.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-29"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-29">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://steen.free.fr/relay10/jelbazech.html">"Relay 10/R \xe2\x80\x93 Jelbazech"</a>. Steen.free.fr. 2004-08-28<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2010-11-06</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=Relay+10%2FR+%E2%80%93+Jelbazech&amp;rft.date=2004-08-28&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Steen.free.fr&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fsteen.free.fr%2Frelay10%2Fjelbazech.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-30"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/\xc9\x99/</span> can occur only in unstressed syllables, and it tends to be rounded <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[\xc9\xb5\xcc\x9e]</span>; it is replaced by <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[\xc3\xb8]</span> when stressed.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-31"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/\xc9\x90/</span> developed as the allophone of <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/a/</span> before nasals and under low stress, and the two are still nearly in complementary distribution. A few minimal pairs like <i>falamos</i> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/f\xc9\x90\xcb\x88l\xc9\x90mu\xca\x83/</span> "we speak" vs. <i>fal\xc3\xa1mos</i> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/f\xc9\x90\xcb\x88lamu\xca\x83/</span> "we spoke" seem to clearly indicate that <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/\xc9\x90/</span> must be a phoneme, but other analyses are possible. <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/\xc9\xa8/</span>, which developed from earlier <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/e/</span> in unstressed syllables, is even more doubtful.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Haase, Martin. 2000. Reorganization of a gender system: The Central Italian neuters. in <i>Gender in Grammar and Cognition</i>, ed. by Barbara Unterbeck et al., pp. 221-236. Berlin: Mouton De Gruyter</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-harris-vincent-33"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-harris-vincent_33-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-harris-vincent_33-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-harris-vincent_33-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-harris-vincent_33-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Harris, Martin; Vincent, Nigel (1988). <i>The Romance Languages</i>. London: Routledge.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.au=Vincent%2C+Nigel&amp;rft.aufirst=Martin&amp;rft.aulast=Harris&amp;rft.btitle=The+Romance+Languages&amp;rft.date=1988&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-kibler-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-kibler_34-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Kibler, William W. (1984). <i>An introduction to Old French</i>. New York: Modern Language Association of America.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.aufirst=William+W.&amp;rft.aulast=Kibler&amp;rft.btitle=An+introduction+to+Old+French&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Modern+Language+Association+of+America&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-35"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Henri_Wittmann" title="Henri Wittmann">Henri Wittmann</a>. <cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.nou-la.org/ling/1998a-fpparis.pdf">"<span style="padding-left:0.2em;">"</span>Le fran\xc3\xa7ais de Paris dans le fran\xc3\xa7ais des Am\xc3\xa9riques.<span style="padding-right:0.2em;">"</span>"</a> <span style="font-size:85%;">(PDF)</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=%22Le+fran%C3%A7ais+de+Paris+dans+le+fran%C3%A7ais+des+Am%C3%A9riques.%22&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nou-la.org%2Fling%2F1998a-fpparis.pdf&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>&#160;<small>(52.1&#160;KB)</small>, <i>Proceedings of the International Congress of Linguists</i> 16.0416 (Paris, 20\xe2\x80\x9325 juillet 1997). Oxford: Pergamon (CD edition).</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-36"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-36">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>ipse</i> originally meant "self", as in <i>ego</i> <i>ipse</i> or <i>egomet</i> <i>ipse</i> "I myself". <i>ipse</i> later shifted to mean "the" (still reflected in Sardinian and in the Catalan spoken in the <a href="/wiki/Balearic_Islands" title="Balearic Islands">Balearic Islands</a>), and still later came to be a demonstrative pronoun. From <i>-met</i> <i>ipse</i> the emphatic (<a href="/wiki/Superlative" class="mw-redirect" title="Superlative">superlative</a>) form <i>metipsimum</i> was created, later evolving into <i>medisimum</i> and eventually Spanish <i>mismo</i>, French <i>m\xc3\xaame</i>, Italian <i>medesimo</i>, which replaced both Latin <i>ipse</i> "self" and <i>idem</i> "same". The alternative form <i>metipse</i> eventually produced Catalan <i>mateix</i>, <a href="/wiki/Galician-Portuguese" title="Galician-Portuguese">Galician-Portuguese</a> <i>med\xc3\xaas</i>. The more frequent Italian equivalent, however, is <i>stesso</i>, derived from the combination <i>istum</i>-<i>ipsum</i>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-accademiadellacrusca.it-37"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-accademiadellacrusca.it_37-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-accademiadellacrusca.it_37-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.accademiadellacrusca.it/faq/faq_risp.php?id=4697&amp;ctg_id=93">Accademia della Crusca <i>On the use of the passato remoto</i> (in Italian)</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20060607220030/http://www.accademiadellacrusca.it/faq/faq_risp.php?id=4697&amp;ctg_id=93">Archived</a> June 7, 2006, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-38"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-38">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Cf. <i>auret</i> "she had" &lt; Latin <i>habuerat</i>, <i>voldrent</i> "they wanted" &lt; Latin <i>voluerant</i>. Not clearly distinct in meaning from the first (normal) preterite, cf. the parallel lines <i>por o fut presentede</i> "for this reason she was presented" (<i>fut</i> = first preterite, from Latin <i>fuit</i>) vs. <i>por o\'s furet morte</i> "for these reasons she was killed" (<i>furet</i> = second preterite, from Latin <i>fuerat</i>) in the same poem.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-39"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Paden, William D. 1998. <i>An Introduction to Old Occitan</i>. Modern Language Association of America. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-87352-293-1" title="Special:BookSources/0-87352-293-1">0-87352-293-1</a>. (NEED PAGE NUMBER)</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-40"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0057:entry=spa/qh"><span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">\xcf\x83\xcf\x80\xce\xac\xce\xb8\xce\xb7</span></a>. <a href="/wiki/Henry_Liddell" title="Henry Liddell">Liddell, Henry George</a>; <a href="/wiki/Robert_Scott_(philologist)" title="Robert Scott (philologist)">Scott, Robert</a>; <i><a href="/wiki/A_Greek%E2%80%93English_Lexicon" title="A Greek\xe2\x80\x93English Lexicon">A Greek\xe2\x80\x93English Lexicon</a></i> at the <a href="/wiki/Perseus_Project" title="Perseus Project">Perseus Project</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-41"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-41">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Harper, Douglas. "<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&amp;search=spatha">spatha</a>". Online Etymology Dictionary.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-42"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-42">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0057:entry=ka/ra1"><span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">\xce\xba\xce\xac\xcf\x81\xce\xb1</span></a>&#160;in <a href="/wiki/Henry_Liddell" title="Henry Liddell">Liddell</a> and <a href="/wiki/Robert_Scott_(philologist)" title="Robert Scott (philologist)">Scott</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-43"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0057:entry=ko/lafos"><span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">\xce\xba\xcf\x8c\xce\xbb\xce\xb1\xcf\x86\xce\xbf\xcf\x82</span></a>&#160;in <a href="/wiki/Henry_Liddell" title="Henry Liddell">Liddell</a> and <a href="/wiki/Robert_Scott_(philologist)" title="Robert Scott (philologist)">Scott</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-44"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-44">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Harper, Douglas. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.etymonline.com/?term=coup">"coup"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Online_Etymology_Dictionary" title="Online Etymology Dictionary">Online Etymology Dictionary</a></i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.atitle=coup&amp;rft.au=Harper%2C+Douglas&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Online+Etymology+Dictionary&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.etymonline.com%2F%3Fterm%3Dcoup&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-45"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0057:entry=kata/1"><span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">\xce\xba\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xac</span></a>&#160;in <a href="/wiki/Henry_Liddell" title="Henry Liddell">Liddell</a> and <a href="/wiki/Robert_Scott_(philologist)" title="Robert Scott (philologist)">Scott</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-46"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Harper, Douglas. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.etymonline.com/?term=-ize">"-ize"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Online_Etymology_Dictionary" title="Online Etymology Dictionary">Online Etymology Dictionary</a></i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.atitle=-ize&amp;rft.au=Harper%2C+Douglas&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Online+Etymology+Dictionary&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.etymonline.com%2F%3Fterm%3D-ize&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-47"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-47">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Harper, Douglas. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.etymonline.com/?term=-ist">"-ist"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Online_Etymology_Dictionary" title="Online Etymology Dictionary">Online Etymology Dictionary</a></i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.atitle=-ist&amp;rft.au=Harper%2C+Douglas&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Online+Etymology+Dictionary&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.etymonline.com%2F%3Fterm%3D-ist&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-48"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Wolf Dietrich, \xe2\x80\x9cGriechisch und Romanisch\xe2\x80\x9d, <i>Lexikon der romanistischen Linguistik</i>, vol 7: <i>Kontakt, Migration und Kunstsprachen: Kontrastivit\xc3\xa4t, Klassifikation und Typologie</i>, eds. G\xc3\xbcnter Holtus, Michael Metzeltin &amp; Christian Schmitt (T\xc3\xbcbingen: Max Niemeyer, 1998), 121-34:123-4.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-49"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Originally formal, now equalizing or informal.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-50"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Likewise Spanish <i>usted</i> &lt; <i>vuestra merced</i>, Catalan <i>vost\xc3\xa8</i> &lt; <i>vostra merc\xc3\xa8</i>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-51"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-51">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Note that the current Portuguese spelling (<a href="/wiki/Portuguese_Language_Orthographic_Agreement_of_1990" title="Portuguese Language Orthographic Agreement of 1990">Portuguese Language Orthographic Agreement of 1990</a>) abolished the use of the diaeresis for this purpose.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-52"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-52">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Pope (1934).</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-53"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-53">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Allen (2003) states: "There appears to have been no great difference in quality between long and short <i>a</i>, but in the case of the close and mid vowels (<i>i</i> and <i>u</i>, <i>e</i> and <i>o</i>) the long appear to have been appreciably closer than the short." He then goes on to the historical development, quotations from various authors (from around the second century AD), as well as evidence from older inscriptions where "e" stands for normally short <i>i</i>, and "i" for long <i>e</i>, etc.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-54"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-54">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Technically, Sardinian is one of the <a href="/wiki/Southern_Romance_languages" title="Southern Romance languages">Southern Romance languages</a>. The same vowel outcome occurred in a small strip running across southern Italy (the <i>Lausberg Zone</i>), and is thought to have occurred in the Romance languages of northern Africa.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Palmer-55"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Palmer_55-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Palmer (1954).</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-56"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-56">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>cauda</i> would produce French **<i>choue</i>, Italian <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">*/k\xc9\x94da/</span>, Occitan **<i>cauda</i>, Romanian **<i>caud\xc4\x83</i>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-kaze1991-57"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-kaze1991_57-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Kaze, Jeffery W. (1991). "Metaphony and Two Models for the Description of Vowel Systems". <i>Phonology</i>. <b>8</b> (1): 163\xe2\x80\x93170. <a href="/wiki/JSTOR" title="JSTOR">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.jstor.org/stable/4420029">4420029</a>. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1017%2Fs0952675700001329">10.1017/s0952675700001329</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.atitle=Metaphony+and+Two+Models+for+the+Description+of+Vowel+Systems&amp;rft.aufirst=Jeffery+W.&amp;rft.aulast=Kaze&amp;rft.date=1991&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.jtitle=Phonology&amp;rft.pages=163-170&amp;rft.volume=8&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F4420029&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1017%2Fs0952675700001329&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-58"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-58">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Calabrese, Andrea. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://homepages.uconn.edu/~anc02008/Papers/METAPHONY.pdf">"Metaphony"</a> <span style="font-size:85%;">(PDF)</span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2012-05-15</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrea&amp;rft.aulast=Calabrese&amp;rft.btitle=Metaphony&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fhomepages.uconn.edu%2F~anc02008%2FPapers%2FMETAPHONY.pdf&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-59"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-59">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://personales.uniovi.es/web/ariasal/">\xc3\x81lvaro Arias. <i>El morfema de \xe2\x80\x98neutro de materia\xe2\x80\x99 en asturiano.</i> Santiago de Compostela, Universidade de Santiago de Compostela, 1999, I Premio \xc2\xabD\xc3\xa1maso Alonso\xc2\xbb de Investigaci\xc3\xb3n Filol\xc3\xb3gica.</a></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-penny1994-60"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-penny1994_60-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-penny1994_60-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Penny, Ralph (1994). "Continuity and Innovation in Romance: Metaphony and Mass-Noun Reference in Spain and Italy". <i>The Modern Language Review</i>. <b>89</b> (2): 273\xe2\x80\x93281. <a href="/wiki/JSTOR" title="JSTOR">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.jstor.org/stable/3735232">3735232</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.atitle=Continuity+and+Innovation+in+Romance%3A+Metaphony+and+Mass-Noun+Reference+in+Spain+and+Italy&amp;rft.aufirst=Ralph&amp;rft.aulast=Penny&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Modern+Language+Review&amp;rft.pages=273-281&amp;rft.volume=89&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F3735232&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-AAC-61"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-AAC_61-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://personales.uniovi.es/web/ariasal/">\xc3\x81lvaro Arias. \xc2\xabLa armonizaci\xc3\xb3n voc\xc3\xa1lica en fonolog\xc3\xada funcional (de lo sintagm\xc3\xa1tico en fonolog\xc3\xada a prop\xc3\xb3sito de dos casos de metafon\xc3\xada hisp\xc3\xa1nica)\xc2\xbb, <i>Moenia</i> 11 (2006): 111\xe2\x80\x93139.</a></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-62"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-62">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Note that the outcome of <i>-am -em -om</i> would be the same regardless of whether lengthening occurred, and that <i>-im</i> was already rare in Classical Latin, and appears to have barely survived in Proto-Romance. The only likely survival is in "-teen" numerals such as <i>tr\xc4\x93decim</i> "thirteen" &gt; Italian <i>tredici</i>. This favors the vowel-lengthening hypothesis <i>-im</i> &gt; <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/\xc4\xa9\xcb\x90/</span> &gt; <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/i/</span>; but notice unexpected <i>decem</i> &gt; Italian <i>dieci</i> (rather than expected <i>*diece</i>). It is possible that <i>dieci</i> comes from *<i>decim</i>, which analogically replaced <i>decem</i> based on the <i>-decim</i> ending; but it is also possible that the final /i/ in <i>dieci</i> represents an irregular development of some other sort and that the process of analogy worked in the other direction.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-63"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-63">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Latin forms are attested; <i>metipsissimus</i> is the superlative of the formative -<i>metipse</i>, found for example in <i>egometipse</i> "myself in person"</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-64"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-64">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Ralph Penny, <i>A History of the Spanish Language</i>, 2nd edn. (Cambridge: Cambridge UP, 2002), 144.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-65"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Aurelio M. Espinosa, "Metipsimus in Spanish and French", <i><a href="/wiki/Modern_Language_Association#Activities" title="Modern Language Association">PMLA</a></i>, vol. 26, no. 2 (1911): 356\xe2\x80\x93378.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-66"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-66">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Formerly \xe2\x9f\xa8q\xc3\xbc\xe2\x9f\xa9 in Brazilian Portuguese</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-67"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-67">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Formerly \xe2\x9f\xa8g\xc3\xbc\xe2\x9f\xa9 in Brazilian Portuguese</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-68"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-68">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ditzionariu.org/home.asp?lang=sar">"Ditzion\xc3\xa0riu Online"</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2013-09-14</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=Ditzion%C3%A0riu+Online&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ditzionariu.org%2Fhome.asp%3Flang%3Dsar&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-69"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-69">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://italian.about.com/od/sicilian/a/aa050405d_3.htm">"Sicilian\xe2\x80\x93English Dictionary"</a>. Italian.about.com. 2010-06-15<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2010-11-06</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARomance+languages&amp;rft.btitle=Sicilian%E2%80%93English+Dictionary&amp;rft.date=2010-06-15&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Italian.about.com&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fitalian.about.com%2Fod%2Fsicilian%2Fa%2Faa050405d_3.htm&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-70"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-70">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" hre